You can disable this shortcut. In JupyterLab "Advanced Settings Editor", select Keboard Shortcuts and add:

```json
{
    "shortcuts": [
        {
            "args": {},
            "command": "documentsearch:start",
            "keys": [
                "Accel F"
            ],
            "selector": ".jp-mod-searchable",
            "disabled": true
        }
    ]
}
```

to the JSON field, which should disable cmd-F for search. For me, this results in regular browser search on cmd-F in both notebook 7 and JupyterLab.

(alternately, write this same JSON to `~/.jupyter/lab/user-settings/@jupyterlab/shortcuts-extension/shortcuts.jupyterlab-settings`).

The following is a workaround, activated by `Alt-Shfit-Z`. I added it as a userscript, but it probably should work in a `%%javascript` cell.


```javascript
//
// Jupyter 7: add keyboard shortcut Alt-Shift-Z to Zen Mode
// - Alt-Shift-Z is used instead of Ctrl-Shift-Z
//   because in regular Jupyter cells, one cannot intercept
//   Ctrl-Shift keys (probably caught by Jupyter)
//
function addKeyboardShortCutToZenMode() {
  function goFullscreen() {
    // the main notebook body (without menu, toolbars, side panels)
    document.querySelector('#main-panel > div > div.jp-Notebook').requestFullscreen();
  }
  window.addEventListener('keydown', (evt) => {
    if (evt.altKey && evt.shiftKey && evt.code == 'KeyZ') {
      goFullscreen();
    }
  });
}
addKeyboardShortCutToZenMode();
```

